==English==

===Etymology===
Borrowed from {{bor|en|la|depretiare|depretiare, depretiatus}}, from {{m|la|de-}} + {{m|la|pretium||price}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|en|/dɪˈpɹiːʃɪeɪt/}}
** {{audio|en|LL-Q1860 (eng)-Vealhurl-depreciate.wav|Audio (UK)}}

===Verb===
{{en-verb}}

# {{lb|en|transitive}} To lessen in price or estimated value; to lower the worth of.
#* '''1678''', {{w|Ralph Cudworth}}, ''The True Intellectual System of the Universe''
#*: {{...}} which {{...}} some over-severe philosophers may look upon fastidiously, or undervalue and '''depreciate'''.
#* '''1 December, 1783''', {{w|Edmund Burke}}, ''speech on Fox's East India Bill''
#*: To prove that the Americans ought not to be free, we are obliged to '''depreciate''' the value of freedom itself.
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} To decline in value over time.
# {{lb|en|transitive}} To [[belittle]] or [[disparage]].

====Usage notes====
* Do not confuse with {{m|en|deprecate||to disapprove of}}. The meaning of ''deprecate'' has lately been [[encroach]]ing on ''depreciate'' in the sense 'to belittle'.

